                        <p><hi rend="italic">Case at the Hospitals of <name type="place">Alexandria, Va.</name></hi></p><p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 75.&#8212;<name type="person"
                                                key="829">Private James O'Leary</name>, <name
                                                type="organization" key="729">U. S. Inf.</name>,
                                        unattached; admitted <date type="transfer" when="1865-02-23">Feb. 23, 1865</date>, from <name type="hospital" key="209">Washington street prison</name> so nearly moribund that no history could be obtained from him. His eyes were fixed and vacant, skin cold, dry and livid.  He died <date type="death" when="1865-02-23">soon after admission</date>.   <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi>
                                        examination: The meningeal vessels were pale and watery, as
                                        were those of the vascular processes in the lateral
                                        ventricles; serum was effused beneath the arachnoid and
                                        lymph at the vertex and over the base of the brain; the
                                        cerebral substance was pale, soft and an&#230;mic, and
                                        the ventricles contained serum with some lymph.
                                        The spinal cord was soft. The glands at the root of each
                                        lung contained calcareous deposits. The liver was large; the
                                        spleen soft and pulpy; the bladder largely distended.</p>                        
